p target\n- [ ] Create help target as default goal (.DEFAULT_GOAL := help)\n- [ ] Implement help text with color coding (BLUE, GREEN, YELLOW, NC)\n- [ ] Extract target descriptions from makefile comments\n- [ ] Display all available targets with descriptions\n- [ ] Display configurable variables with default values\n- [ ] Ensure help target is readable and well-formatted\n- [ ] Test help target: `make help`\n- [ ] Verify all targets are listed\n- [ ] Verify all variables are shown\n- [ ] Add usage examples in help text\n\n**Verification**: `make help` displays comprehensive, well-formatted help information\n\n---\n\n### Task 4: Implement Go binary build targets\n- [ ] Create build-go target to build all Go binaries\n- [ ] Create individual targets for each binary:\n  - `build-agentd` for cmd/agentd/main.go\n  - `build-picod` for cmd/picod/main.go\n  - `build-agentcube` for cmd/agentcube/main.go\n  - `build-code-interpreter` for cmd/code-interpreter/main.go\n  - `build-agent-runtime` for cmd/agent-runtime/main.go\n  - `build-agentcube-util` for cmd/agentcube-util/main.go\n- [ ] Use `go build` with proper flags (-ldflags for version info)\n- [ ] Set GOBIN to local build directory\n- [ ] Support platform builds (GOOS, GOARCH variables)\n- [ ] Support cross-compilation\n- [ ] Add build timestamp and git commit to binaries\n- [ ] Ensure build fails on errors\n- [ ] Test each individual binary build\n- [ ] Test `make build-go` builds all binaries\n\n**Verification**: All Go binaries build successfully with version information embedded\n\n---\n\n### Task 5: Implement Go build optimization targets\n- [ ] Create `build-go-race` target with race detector\n- [ ] Create `build-go-debug` target with debug symbols\n- [ ] Create `build-go-release` target with optimizations\n- [ ] Implement build caching support\n- [ ] Add parallel build support for multiple binaries\n- [ ] Create `build-go-fast` target that skips unnecessary steps\n- [ ] Support incremental builds\n- [ ] Add build